# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gene-alley
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gene-alley/1963-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1963 throughout the world.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] The **1963 major league baseball season** began on April 8, 1963.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 29, with the Los Angeles Dodgers and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 60th World Series on October 2 and ended with Game 4 on October 6.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] In the eighth iteration of this World Series matchup, and their first since the Dodgers relocated to Los Angeles from Brooklyn, New York, the Dodgers swept the Yankees in four games, capturing their third championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1959, and second in Los Angeles.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] The Dodgers' stellar pitching staff, anchored by left-hander Sandy Koufax and right-hander Don Drysdale, was so dominant that the vaunted Yankees, despite the presence of sluggers such as Mickey Mantle and Roger Maris in their lineup, never took a lead against Los Angeles the entire Series.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] This was the eighth World Series between the two teams.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Yankees from the 1962 season.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] In a return to the single-game-in-a-season format, the 34th All-Star Game, was held on July 9 at Cleveland Stadium in Cleveland, Ohio, home of the Cleveland Indians.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] The 1963 schedule consisted of 162 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had 10 teams.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 18 games against the other nine teams of their respective league.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place by the American League since the 1961 season and by the National League since the previous season, and would be used until 1969.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 8, featuring four teams.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 29, which saw 16 teams play.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 2 and October 6.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] 1 tie game (0 in AL, 1 in NL), which is not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and was replayed again) occurred during the season.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 2 and ended on October 6 with the Los Angeles Dodgers sweeping the New York Yankees in the 1963 World Series in four games.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] In the American League, the New York Yankees were in the 4th of 5 straight pennant winning years, and, led by MVP Elston Howard, cruised to the American League title by 10.5 games over the 2nd place Chicago White Sox.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League, most experts figured the San Francisco Giants and Los Angeles Dodgers would be locked in another battle for the pennant, much like 1962 when the Giants came from behind and beat the Dodgers in a playoff.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] The Dodgers started slowly, perhaps feeling the hangover effect from blowing the pennant the year before.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] They were 2 games under .500 in early May, and trailed the surprising St.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] Then their pitching asserted itself, and on August 28, the Dodgers led the Giants by 5.5 games and the Cardinals by 6.5 games.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] The Cardinals proceeded to win 19 of their next 20 games and, while the Dodgers didn't exactly slump, they went "only" 14–7 during that same period.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] Louis on September 16 to play the Cardinals in a 3-game series leading by only 1 game.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] With the memory of blowing the 1962 pennant fresh in their minds, the Dodgers proceeded to sweep the Cardinals and take a 4-game lead with 7 games to go.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] The key game was the third one; the Cardinals led 5–1 in the 8th inning and a win would move them back to within 2 games of L.A.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] But the Dodgers got 3 in the 8th and in the top of the 9th, late season call up Dick Nen, in only his 8th major league at bat, hit a pinch hit homer to force extra innings.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] The Cardinals got a leadoff triple from Dick Groat in the 10th but could not score.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] The Dodgers then scored an unearned run in the 13th inning and won, 6–5.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] The disheartened Cardinals then lost their next 3 games as well while the Dodgers won 3 of their next 4 to clinch the pennant with 6 games left.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] In an attempt to create an identity distinguishable from all other teams, Kansas City Athletics owner Charlie Finley changed the team uniforms to kelly green and yellow.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] This tradition of "green and gold" has been preserved to this day, although the kelly green has since been replaced with forest green.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] Finley also changed the Athletics' cleats to white instead of the standard black.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] Coaches and managers were also given white hats, which were dropped when the Athletics adopted new colors in 1993.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] The white cleats were dropped in 2000, but were revived in 2008.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] The New York Mets would play their final game at the Polo Grounds on September 18 against the Philadelphia Phillies, moving into Shea Stadium for the start of the 1964 season.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the final of 78 seasons since 1882 that any iteration of the Polo Grounds featured a major-league team.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] CBS and NBC aired weekend *Game of the Week* broadcasts.
[src:gene-alley/1963-major-league-baseball-season] The All-Star Game and World Series also aired on NBC.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1967 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the 38th midseason exhibition between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and the National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was played on July 11, 1967, at Anaheim Stadium in Anaheim, California, home of the California Angels of the American League.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in a 2–1 15 inning victory for the NL.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] It set the record for the longest All-Star Game by innings, subsequently matched in 2008.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Fifteen coaches and players, denoted in *italics*, would be inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Nine players, denoted in *italics*, would be inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The batting order was determined by each team's manager.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL scored first when Dick Allen, the lead-off batter in the top of the second inning, hit a home run off of AL pitcher Dean Chance.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The AL tied the score in the bottom of the sixth inning.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] With one out, Brooks Robinson hit a home run off of NL relief pitcher Ferguson Jenkins.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The score remained unchanged through the ninth inning, forcing the game into extra innings.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the top of the 15th inning, Tony Pérez hit a one-out home run off of AL pitcher Catfish Hunter, then in his fifth inning of relief, to give the NL a lead it would not relinquish.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Rod Carew became the first (and as of 2008, only) rookie second baseman to start an All-Star Game.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The two teams' pitching staffs combined for 30 strikeouts.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Until 2008, this would be the All-Star Game record for most combined strikeouts in a single game.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Each of the 12 pitchers used by both leagues had at least one strikeout with Ferguson Jenkins leading the way with six strikeouts in three innings of work.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] One year after becoming the first African-American umpire in Major League history, Emmett Ashford became the first African-American umpire to work an All-Star Game.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The pregame ceremonies featured The Lennon Sisters singing the national anthem.
[src:gene-alley/1967-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The ceremonial first pitches were thrown by Red Ruffing and Lloyd Waner, who were inducted that year into the Baseball Hall Of Fame.
[src:gene-alley/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1968 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the 39th playing of the midsummer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:gene-alley/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was held on July 9, 1968, at the Astrodome in Houston, Texas the home of the Houston Astros of the National League, making this the first All-Star Game to be played indoors.
[src:gene-alley/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in the National League defeating the American League 1–0.
[src:gene-alley/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] It is the only All-Star Game played without a run batted in (RBI).
[src:gene-alley/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] This was the first night All-Star Game since 1944.
[src:gene-alley/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Apart from the 1969 game (which was originally scheduled to be played at night but was postponed to the following afternoon due to rain), all subsequent All-Star Games have been played at night.
[src:gene-alley/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The next indoor All-Star Game was eleven years later, at the Kingdome in Seattle.
[src:gene-alley/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The American League was limited to three hits, unable to get a rally going against Don Drysdale, Juan Marichal, Steve Carlton and Tom Seaver, all future Hall of Famers.
[src:gene-alley/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] A first-inning run scored by Willie Mays on a single, an errant pickoff attempt, a wild pitch by Luis Tiant and a double-play ball gave the winning National league the only run they would need.
[src:gene-alley/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Don Wert's eighth-inning double momentarily gave the AL a threat to tie the game, but Seaver struck out the side.
[src:gene-alley/1968-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the ninth, with two out, Jerry Koosman was brought in from the bullpen to face Carl Yastrzemski, whose strikeout ended the game.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] The **1970 major league baseball season** began on April 6, 1970, while the regular season ended on October 1.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Mets from the 1969 season.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] The 41st All-Star Game was held on July 14 at Riverfront Stadium in Cincinnati, Ohio, home of the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] The National League won in 12 innings, 5–4, concluding their eight-season win streak.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] During spring training, the Seattle Pilots moved to Milwaukee, Wisconsin as the Milwaukee Brewers, being the ninth team since 1953 to relocate, and the fifth of American League teams since them.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] Due to stadium issues and the team declaring bankruptcy, the team was sold to a Milwaukee-based group and promptly relocated.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] After having a team for only a single season, Seattle would be without a major league team for seven seasons until the expansion in 1977, with the enfranchisement of the Seattle Mariners.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] The team was tied with the coincidentally named 1901 Milwaukee Brewers (modern-day Baltimore Orioles) as the shortest-tenured team of the American League.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] National League umpires began wearing numbers on the sleeves of their blazers and the new short-sleeved light blue shirts they began wearing (to replace the long sleeved shirts of previous years).
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] The numbers were in alphabetical order (Al Barlick wore #1, Ken Burkhart #2, etc.) and this remained the annual numbering system until the 1979 season when the numbers became permanent regardless of retirements/resignations/firings/etc.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] The 1970 schedule consisted of 162 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had 12 teams.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] Each league was split into two six-team divisions.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 18 games against their five division rivals, totaling 90 games, and 12 games against six interdivision opponents, totaling 72 games.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the previous season and would be used until 1977 in the American League and 1993 in the National League.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 6, featuring four teams.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 1, featuring 22 teams.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] Each League Championship Series took place between October 3 and October 5.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 10 and October 15.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] 1 tie game (1 in AL, 0 in NL), which is not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and was replayed again) occurred during the season.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 3 and ended on October 15 with the Baltimore Orioles defeating the Cincinnati Reds in the 1970 World Series in five games.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] The 1970 season saw three teams move to three new venues.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Phillies would play their final game at Connie Mack Stadium on October 1 against the Montreal Expos, moving into Veterans Stadium for the start of the 1971 season.
[src:gene-alley/1970-major-league-baseball-season] NBC was the exclusive national TV broadcaster of MLB, airing the weekend *Game of the Week*, the All-Star Game, both League Championship Series, and the World Series.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] The **1971 major league baseball season** began on April 5, 1971, while the regular season ended on September 30.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Baltimore Orioles from the 1970 season.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] The 42nd All-Star Game was held on July 13 at Tiger Stadium in Detroit, Michigan, home of the Detroit Tigers.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] The American League won, 6–4, and was the first American League win since the second game of 1962, and their last until 1983.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] This was the final season that the Washington Senators would play in Washington, D.C., as the team would relocate to the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex city of Arlington, Texas, as the Texas Rangers the following season.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] Washington would remain vacant of a major league team for 33 seasons until the Montreal Expos relocated there as the Washington Nationals in 2005.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] This was the final season the majority of MLB teams wore wool flannel uniforms.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] The Pirates and Cardinals wore double knit uniforms of nylon and rayon throughout 1971, and the Orioles gradually phased out flannels, going all-double knit in time for the ALCS.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] By 1973, flannel uniforms completely disappeared from the MLB scene.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] The 1971 schedule consisted of 162 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had 12 teams.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1969 and would be used until 1977 in the American League and 1993 in the National League.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 5, featuring six teams.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 30, featuring 18 teams.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] The National League Championship Series took place between October 2 and October 6, while the American League Championship Series took place between October 3 and October 5.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 9 and October 17.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 2 and ended on October 17 with the Pittsburgh Pirates defeating the Baltimore Orioles in the 1971 World Series in seven games.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the four division races were anticlimactic; the only race was in the NL West between old rivals Los Angeles Dodgers and San Francisco Giants.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] The Giants led by 8.5 games on September 1 but the Dodgers chipped away.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] In mid September, the Dodgers won 8 in a row, including 5 over the Giants to narrow the gap to one game.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] But they could get no closer; ultimately both teams won on the final day of the season and the Giants won the division by 1 game.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Phillies leave Connie Mack Stadium from which they played 33 seasons and opened Veterans Stadium (with the NFL's Philadelphia Eagles), where they would go on to play for 33 seasons through 2003.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] The Washington Senators would play their final game at Robert F.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] Kennedy Memorial Stadium on September 30 against the New York Yankees, relocating to Arlington, Texas at Arlington Stadium as the Texas Rangers for the start of the 1972 season.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] The game was even more notable in that, with the Senators leading the Yankees 7–5 in the top of the 9th inning with one out, fans proceeded to storm and vandalize the field, preventing the game from continuing.
[src:gene-alley/1971-major-league-baseball-season] The Senators were forced to forfeit the game to the Yankees.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] The **1971 National League Championship Series** was a best-of-five series in Major League Baseball’s 1971 postseason that pitted the East Division champion Pittsburgh Pirates against the West Division champion San Francisco Giants.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Pirates won the Series three games to one and won the 1971 World Series against the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Giants did not return to the postseason until 1987.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] This was the third National League Championship Series in all.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] It was the first League Championship Series in either league that was not a sweep for the winning team (Baltimore swept Oakland in the 1971 ALCS).
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] With aces Gaylord Perry and Steve Blass taking the mound for their respective teams, Game 1 looked to be a pitchers' duel.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Pirates struck for two in the top of the third when Dave Cash doubled home Jackie Hernández.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] Cash scored the second run when Richie Hebner grounded to Tito Fuentes at second, but Willie McCovey dropped Fuentes' throw when he attempted to field the ball after having to scramble back to first because Perry didn't cover the bag.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Giants halved the lead in their half of the third when Chris Speier singled, went to second on a Perry sacrifice bunt, and scored on a Ken Henderson single.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] Fuentes and McCovey would redeem themselves in the fifth by each slamming two-run homers off Blass for a 5–2 lead.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] Al Oliver cut the deficit to 5–4 for the Pirates with two-run single in the seventh, but that was it as Perry went the distance for a complete game win.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] In front of an NBC-TV audience, Pirate first baseman Bob Robertson grew into a star in Game 2.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] Robertson smashed three homers, becoming the first to do so in a playoff game.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Giants struck first in the bottom of the first when Tito Fuentes singled off Dock Ellis and scored on a double by Willie Mays.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] After the Pirates tied the game in the second off John Cumberland when Robertson hit a leadoff double and scored on Manny Sanguillén's single, the Giants retook the lead in the bottom half when Chris Speier hit a leadoff double and scored on Ken Henderson's single.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] Robertson's first home run of the game tied the score again in the fourth.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] Sanguillén's single then knocked Cumberland out of the game.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] After a stolen base, Jackie Hernández's RBI single off Jim Barr put the Pirates up 3–2.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] Gene Clines's home run next inning extended their lead to 4–2.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] A pivotal play occurred just prior to the Pirates' 4-run seventh, when Mays, batting in the bottom of the sixth with two out and his team trailing, 4–2, saw his bid for a bases-clearing double grabbed by right fielder Roberto Clemente.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] After a leadoff double and single, Clemente's RBI single off Don Carrithers made it 5–2 Pirates.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] One out later, Robertsons' three-run home run off Ron Bryant extended their lead to 8–2.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] Robertson's third home run in the ninth off of Steve Hamilton made it 9–2.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] A two-run home run from Mays off Bob Miller in the bottom half made it 9–4, but Dave Giusti in relief retired all three batters he faced as the Pirates tied the series heading to Pittsburgh.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Pirates' Bob Johnson and the Giants' Juan Marichal locked into a tight pitcher's duel for eight innings.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] Bob Robertson hit a homer in the second, his then-record fourth of the series.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Giants tied it in the sixth when Ken Henderson singled and scored when third baseman Richie Hebner threw wildly past Robertson at first after fielding a bunt by Tito Fuentes.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] Hebner would atone for the error, however, by slamming a game-winning homer in the eighth off Marichal.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] Dave Giusti came on in the ninth and saved it for Johnson and the Pirates.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] Another anticipated pitching duel between Giants' Gaylord Perry and Pirates' Steve Blass quickly went by the wayside.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] Blass lasted only two innings, giving up five runs.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] Willie McCovey's RBI single with two on in the first gave the Giants a 1–0 lead, but they left the bases loaded.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] In the bottom half, after a leadoff single and double, Roberto Clemente's two-run single put the Pirates up 2–1, but in the second, Chris Speier's leadoff home run tied the game.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] After two singles and two outs, Willie McCovey's three-run home run put the Giants up 5–2, but the Pirates, however, got Blass off the hook in the bottom of the inning.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] Manny Sanguillen singled and 1960 World Series hero Bill Mazeroski, hitting for Blass, also singled.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] Richie Hebner then tied the game with a three-run home run.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] The score stayed at 5–5 until the sixth when Dave Cash singled, moved to second on a groundout, and scored on a Roberto Clemente RBI single.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] Jerry Johnson relieved Perry and after intentionally walking Willie Stargell, Al Oliver's three-run home run made it 9–5 Pirates.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] Meanwhile, Bruce Kison and Dave Giusti pitched the last seven innings of shutout baseball to close out the series and win the pennant for the first time in 11 years.
[src:gene-alley/1971-national-league-championship-series] It is Pittsburgh’s fifth-most recent victory in a postseason series.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] A contact hitter with occasional power, Alley handled the bat well.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] He was an excellent bunter and adept at the hit-and-run maneuver.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] In the field, he had plus range and quickness as well as an accurate throwing arm.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] In the 1966 season, he took part in 128 double plays, third most in major league history and one short of the National League record at the time.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] Alley was born on July 10, 1940, in Richmond, Virginia.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] While still an infant, Alley's father died in a car accident, and he and his three siblings were raised by his mother.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] He was a member of the Alley Family in his paternal decent.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] He attended Hermitage High School in Henrico, Virginia.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] Alley had hoped to receive a basketball scholarship to attend the University of Virginia, but the sum offered was insufficient.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] Instead, the 18-year old Alley signed to play baseball with the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] In 1959, the Pirates assigned Alley to the Dubuque Packers of the Class-D Midwest League.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] He had a .287 batting average (his highest in the minor leagues) with 15 home runs, and a .922 fielding percentage at shortstop, his principal position.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] Because of a recurring problem with his throwing arm, he did not play shortstop for the next three years.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] Alley remained in the Pirates minor league system until 1963, playing third base in 1960 (.932 fielding percentage), and second base in 1961 (.933 fielding percentage) and 1962 (.969 combined fielding percentage between Single-A and Triple-A baseball).
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] In 1963, he was promoted Triple-A baseball with the Columbus Jets of the International League.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] He played exclusively at shortstop, where he had a .963 fielding percentage along with a .244 batting average, 19 home runs, 61 runs batted in (RBI) and 76 runs scored in 146 games.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] Alley played briefly for the Pirates at the end of the 1963 season, and then played in 81 games for the Pirates in 1964, hitting only .211, but with a fielding percentage at shortstop of .966 in 61 games at that position.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] He was a frequent backup to starting shortstop Ducky Schofield.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] In 1965, he started 40 games at second base for the injured Bill Mazeroski, and then 102 games at shortstop after Mazeroski's return.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] He had a .968 fielding percentage at shortstop and .974 at second base.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] He hit .252, with five home runs, 47 runs and 47 RBIs.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] He was fourth in the NL in fielding percentage by a shortstop.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] 1966 was his first full year at shortstop.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] He had a .979 fielding percentage (second in the league behind Chico Cardénas' .980), and led all National League shortstops in turning double plays with 128.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] He received the Gold Glove Award for NL shortstops.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] In the same year, Mazeroski set the all-time double play record for second basemen in a season with 161.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] The Pirates as a team turned 215 double plays, the second most in baseball history after the record 217 set by the 1949 Philadelphia Athletics (as of 2023).
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] Alley also hit for a career high .299 batting average, had a career high with 88 runs scored, and his 20 sacrifice hits were second in the NL.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] In 1967, Alley led the league's shortstops again in double plays with 105, as well as leading the league's shortstops in putouts (257) and was second in assists (500).
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] He was also selected to the NL All-Star team for the first time.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] He batted .287, and had a career high 55 RBIs.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] Alley made the NL All-Star a second time in 1968.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] From 1965 to 1968 he was in the top four NL players in assists.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] In 1966 and 1967, *The Sporting News* named him to its All-Star Team.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] Alley and Mazeroski both received Gold Glove Awards in 1966 and 1967, along with their teammate Roberto Clemente.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] They also joined a select list of eight shortstop-second baseman duos to each win a Gold Glove the same season more than once while playing together.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] Alley was on Pirates teams that won their division in 1970 through 1972, and had the NL's best record in 1971 and 1972.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] Shoulder and knee problems ultimately ended Alley's career early.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] Alley developed a sore throwing arm shortly before the 1967 All-Star Game that never fully healed.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] In 1969, he played only 82 games and was on the disabled list for 29 days, though he still had a .977 fielding percentage and 21-game hitting streak.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] He originally injured his knee in 1969 when he suffered a collision on a play while covering first base in a game against the Houston Astros, leading to multiple surgeries.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] A knee injury suffered late in the 1971 season subsequently required surgery, and limited his participation in the 1971 postseason playoffs and World Series.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] On September 2, 1970, Alley hit an inside-the-park grand slam at Jarry Park Stadium in Montreal, against the Montreal Expos.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] With the bases loaded, facing Carl Morton, Alley hit a line drive which landed in front of center fielder Boots Day, who slipped on the wet grass.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] The ball rolled all the way to the wall in deepest center field, and all the baserunners and Alley scored.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] 1973 was his final year, appearing in 76 games altogether, and 56 in the field at either shortstop or third base.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] Alley worked for a printing company in Richmond after his retirement from baseball.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] In 1998, Alley was inducted into the Virginia Sports Hall of Fame.
[src:gene-alley/gene-alley] In 2013, he received the Paul Keyes RBI (Richmond Baseball Impact) Award, given annually to a person making a significant contribution to baseball within or around the Richmond community.
